<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=15125&amp;p=183062#p183062</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=15125&amp;p=183062#p183062"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Is it possible to emulate an NTSC image in GIMP?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=15125&amp;p=183062#p183062"><![CDATA[
If you can't use blargg's snes_ntsc for whatever reason, here's my recipe for approximate NTSC simulation entirely inside GIMP:<br /><br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Image &gt; Mode &gt; RGB<br />You can't apply most filters in indexed mode.</li><li>Image &gt; Scale Image, factor 200%, interpolation None (i.e. nearest neighbor)<br />Horizontally because each pixel lasts 2/3 of a color subcarrier period, and vertically because each of two fields has its own phase.</li><li>Filters &gt; Distorts &gt; Video, 3x3, additive off, rotated on<br />This encodes the image using pixel-sequential RGB, which has similar but not identical properties to the YUV/YIQ QAM that NTSC uses, with a phase offset from one row to the next similar to that of the NES PPU and Super NES S-PPU.</li><li>Filters &gt; Generic &gt; Convolution Matrix, center row [0 1 1 1 0], divisor 1, offset 0, normalize off<br />This decodes pixel-sequential RGB.</li><li>Filters &gt; Blur &gt; Pixelize, width 1, height 2<br />This blends the even and odd fields.</li><li>Image &gt; Scale, width 114%, height 100%, interpolation Linear<br />This corrects the pixel aspect ratio. </li></ol><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu Nov 17, 2016 9:29 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
